## Chapter 2: Mathematical Preliminaries

### 2.1 Measure Spaces and States

Let \((\Omega, \mathcal{F}, \mu_0)\) be a σ‑finite measure space. A **probability density** is a measurable function \(f: \Omega \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}\) with \(\int f \, d\mu_0 = 1\). Denote \(\mathcal{P}(\Omega)\) the set of densities. The **projective space** \(\mathbb{P}(\mathcal{P}) = \mathcal{P} / \sim\) where \(f \sim \lambda f\) for any \(\lambda > 0\) is a homogeneous space for positive operators.

In non‑commutative probability, the role of densities is played by **states** on a von Neumann algebra \(\mathcal{A}\). A state is a positive linear functional \(\omega: \mathcal{A} \to \mathbb{C}\) with \(\omega(1)=1\). The space of states is denoted \(\mathcal{S}(\mathcal{A})\). For commutative \(\mathcal{A} = L^\infty(\Omega)\), states correspond to probability measures via the Riesz representation theorem. The faithful normal reference state \(\omega_0\) corresponds to the measure \(\mu_0\).

### 2.2 Kernels and Completely Positive Maps

A **kernel** on \(\Omega\) is a measurable function \(K: \Omega \times \Omega \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}\) with \(\int K(x,y) \, d\mu_0(x) < \infty\) a.e. in \(y\). The associated integral operator on \(L^1\) is \((K f)(x) = \int K(x,y) f(y) \, d\mu_0(y)\). If \(\int K(x,y) \, d\mu_0(x) = 1\) for all \(y\), \(K\) is a **Markov kernel** and preserves probability densities. The **Schur test** (see Appendix A) provides sufficient conditions for boundedness on \(L^1\).

In the non‑commutative setting, we replace kernels by **completely positive** (CP) maps. A linear map \(\Phi: \mathcal{A} \to \mathcal{A}\) is CP if for all \(n \ge 1\) and all matrices \([a_{ij}] \in M_n(\mathcal{A})\), the matrix \([\Phi(a_{ij})]\) is positive. If \(\Phi(1)=1\), it is **unital**. A CP unital map is the non‑commutative analogue of a Markov kernel. The **dual** map \(\Phi_*: \mathcal{S}(\mathcal{A}) \to \mathcal{S}(\mathcal{A})\) is defined by \((\Phi_* \omega)(a) = \omega(\Phi(a))\). For a state \(\rho\) represented by a density matrix (with respect to \(\omega_0\)), the dual corresponds to the predual action.

### 2.3 Information Geometry: From Fisher–Rao to Bures

The **Kullback–Leibler divergence**  
\[
D_{\text{KL}}(f \| g) = \int f \log \frac{f}{g} \, d\mu_0
\]  
behaves as a squared distance locally. Its Hessian defines the **Fisher–Rao metric** on \(\mathcal{P}(\Omega)\). For finite \(\Omega\), the metric is \(g_{ij} = \delta_{ij}/p_i\).

For quantum states (density matrices \(\rho,\sigma\)), the natural distance is the **Bures distance**:  
\[
d_{\text{Bures}}(\rho,\sigma)^2 = 2\left(1 - \operatorname{Tr}\sqrt{\sqrt{\rho}\,\sigma\,\sqrt{\rho}}\right).
\]  
Its infinitesimal form gives the **Bures metric**, which reduces to the Fisher–Rao metric when \(\rho\) and \(\sigma\) commute. The Bures metric is the quantum analogue of the Fisher–Rao metric and will be used to study the geometry of NCCOs in the non‑commutative setting.

### 2.4 Bregman Divergences and Projections

For a strictly convex differentiable function \(\Phi\), the **Bregman divergence** is  
\[
D_\Phi(p,q) = \Phi(p) - \Phi(q) - \Phi'(q)(p-q).
\]  
For \(\Phi(x)=x\log x - x\), we recover \(D_{\text{KL}}\). The **Bregman projection** of a point \(f\) onto a convex set \(\mathcal{M}\) is the unique minimizer \(f^* \in \mathcal{M}\) of \(D_\Phi(f,f^*)\). For the KL divergence, this is the **information projection** (I‑projection). In the non‑commutative setting, the **Umegaki relative entropy**  
\[
S(\rho \| \sigma) = \operatorname{Tr}(\rho(\log \rho - \log \sigma))
\]  
plays the role of a Bregman divergence and generates the Bures metric via its second derivative.

