### 6.4 Complexity Analysis (Planned)

Let \(\rho\) be the target state after a sequence of NCCOs, and let \(\hat{\rho}_N\) be the Monte Carlo estimate from \(N\) samples. The standard error scales as  
\[
\operatorname{SE}(\hat{\rho}_N) \propto \sqrt{\frac{\tau_{\text{int}}}{N}} \cdot \sigma,
\]  
where \(\sigma\) is the variance of the observable and \(\tau_{\text{int}}\) is the integrated autocorrelation time. For non‑commuting kernels, the geometry of the state space is curved, leading to **increased autocorrelation** because the Markov chain must explore a more complex landscape. We would aim to show that  
\[
\tau_{\text{int}} \propto \frac{1}{\mathcal{I}} \quad \text{in the limit of small order‑sensitivity},
\]  
i.e., the sampling efficiency degrades as the order‑sensitivity becomes small. This links the physical quantumness (commutator) to computational cost.

