### Appendix G: Details of the Van Vleck–Maslov Semiclassical Analysis

We expand on the semiclassical calculation for the minisuperspace kernel. The kernel is  
\[
K(q_2,q_1) = \int_{q(\tau_1)=q_1}^{q(\tau_2)=q_2} e^{i S[q]/\hbar} \mathcal{D}q.
\]  
In the limit \(\hbar\to 0\), the path integral is dominated by stationary points of the action. The leading contribution is given by the Van Vleck–Gutzwiller formula:
\[
K(q_2,q_1) \sim \sum_{\text{classical paths}} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi i \hbar}} \left| \det \left( -\frac{\partial^2 S_{\text{cl}}}{\partial q_1 \partial q_2} \right) \right|^{1/2} e^{i S_{\text{cl}}/\hbar - i\pi \nu/2},
\]  
where \(\nu\) is the Maslov index (the number of caustics encountered). The prefactor is derived from the Gaussian integral around the classical path. The composition of two such kernels involves an integral over the intermediate point \(q\); by the method of stationary phase, the combined prefactor is the product of the individual prefactors, and the Maslov index adds. If the order of constraints is swapped, the classical paths may be different, leading to different prefactors and Maslov indices. The commutator picks up the difference between the two orders.

For Dirac observables, the two orders correspond to the same classical path (because the constraints commute), so the prefactors and Maslov indices are identical, and the commutator vanishes.

